1 (g) Nothing in this Article shall authorize the Commission to establish, require, or enforce
2 a maximum or minimum payout or hold percentage upon any pari-mutuel wagering licensee.
3 (h) All of the following persons are prohibited from engaging in pari-mutuel wagering:
4 (1) Any person under the age of 21.
5 (2) Any person who has requested and not revoked a voluntary exclusion
6 designation pursuant to G.S. 18C-922.
7 (3) Any person who has been adjudicated by law as prohibited from engaging in
8 pari-mutuel wagering.
9 (4) Any member or employee of the Commission deemed ineligible to place a
10 pari-mutuel wager in this State by the Commission's rules or policies.
11 (5) With respect to a horse race, any jockey or driver of a horse competing in the
12 horse race.
13 (i) In addition to other penalties and means of enforcement available, the occurrence of
14 any pari-mutuel wagering not licensed under this Article is hereby declared to be a public
15 nuisance, and the Commission or the district attorney exercising jurisdiction over the area of such
16 prohibited activity may obtain an injunction against the same in a court of competent jurisdiction.
17 "§ 18C-1003. Legacy track licenses.
18 (a) The Commission shall award two legacy track licenses if it receives two or more
19 qualifying applications. The Commission may award one legacy track license if only one
20 applicant applies or if only one applicant is qualified. If no applicant is qualified, the Commission
21 shall not award any legacy track license. In the event the Commission awards one legacy track
22 license or none, it shall accept applications for any remaining legacy track licenses after
23 providing 30 days' notice and not more than six months after its decision to award one legacy
24 track license or deny all applications.
25 (b) No person may apply for a legacy track license unless it or its affiliate, directly or
26 indirectly, at the time of the application, controls a horse track in this State that meets the
27 requirements to be a legacy track.
28 (c) The Commission shall not grant a legacy track license to any applicant if any of the
29 applicant's key persons are determined to be unsuitable because one of more of the following is
30 true with respect to a key person:
31 (1) The key person has been convicted by a judicial court of competent
32 jurisdiction in any jurisdiction, without further opportunity to appeal, of any
33 crime of moral turpitude, embezzlement, or larceny, or any violation of any
34 law pertaining to illegal gaming or gambling.
35 (2) In the immediate 10 years prior to the submission of the application, the key
36 person has been convicted by a judicial court of competent jurisdiction in any
37 jurisdiction, without further opportunity to appeal, of any crime that is or
38 would be a felony in this State.
39 (3) The key person has been identified in the published reports of any federal or
40 state legislative or executive body as being a member or associate of organized
41 crime.
42 (4) The key person has been placed and remains in the custody of any federal,
43 State, or local law enforcement authority.
44 (5) Had a racing or gaming license revoked in another jurisdiction after an
45 adversarial hearing and judicial review, if such grounds of revocation would
46 have been grounds for revoking the license in this State.
47 (d) Every application to the Commission for a legacy track license must include all of the
48 following:
49 (1) The range of contemplated types and modes of horse races to take place at the
50 legacy track.
