8 "§ 18C-1006. Pari-mutuel wagering device supplier license.
9 (a) A pari-mutuel wagering device supplier license shall be required to sell any
10 pari-mutuel wagering device or totalizator to any legacy track operator and to any startup track
11 operator.
12 (b) The Commission may issue a pari-mutuel wagering device supplier license to a
13 qualified applicant for such license whether or not such applicant also holds another license
14 issued pursuant to this Article.
15 (c) At the request of an applicant for a pari-mutuel wagering device supplier, the
16 Commission may issue a provisional pari-mutuel wagering device supplier license to the
17 applicant so long as the applicant has submitted a completed application in accordance with this
18 section. A provisional license issued under this subsection expires on the date provided by the
19 Commission.
20 (d) An applicant for a pari-mutuel wagering device supplier license shall complete and
21 submit an application on a form prescribed by the Commission and a licensing fee of thirty
22 thousand dollars ($30,000). If the application is denied, the licensing fee shall be refunded, minus
23 five percent (5%) of the licensing fee which shall be used by the Commission to offset associated
24 expenses in reviewing the application. In the application, the Commission shall require applicants
25 to disclose the identity of each of the following:
26 (1) Each key person of the applicant who directly owns ten percent (10%) or more
27 of the applicant.
28 (2) Each holding, intermediary, or parent company that directly owns fifteen
29 percent (15%) or more of the applicant.
30 (3) The applicant's board appointed CEO and CFO, or the equivalent as
31 determined by the Commission.
32 (4) Any other information the Commission may deem necessary.
33 (e) The Commission shall conduct a background investigation on the applicant, key
34 persons of the applicant, and current employees of the applicant, as deemed necessary by the
35 Commission. The background investigation shall include a credit history check, a tax record
36 check, and a criminal history record check. In the event an applicant and its key persons have
37 had a completed criminal history record check in the 12 months prior to the application, the
38 Commission may, in its discretion, accept the results of that prior criminal history record check
39 upon submission of an affidavit that there has been no change in criminal history since the prior
40 criminal history record check in this or any other state. The Commission may not award a license
41 if the applicant or a key person of the applicant has been convicted of a felony or any gambling
42 offense in any state or federal court of the United States within 10 years of application or renewal.
43 (f) An applicant for licensure and any key person deemed necessary by the Commission
44 shall consent to a criminal history record check and shall submit all necessary fingerprints.
45 Refusal to consent to a criminal history record check may constitute grounds for the Commission
46 to deny licensure.
47 (g) The Commission shall review and issue licenses to qualified applicants within 60 days
48 of receipt of a completed application. The Commission may extend the review period for an
49 additional 30 days if the background investigation is outstanding.
50 (h) In disclosing the key persons of the pari-mutuel wagering device supplier applicant,
51 the following shall apply:
Page 10 DRS45254-BAxf-11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Governmental created entities, including statutory authorized pension
2 investment boards and Canadian Crown corporations, that are direct or
3 indirect shareholders of an applicant shall be waived in the applicant's
4 disclosure of ownership and control as determined by the Commission.
5 (2) Investment funds or entities registered with the Securities and Exchange
6 Commission, including Investment Advisors and entities under the
7 management of the Securities and Exchange Commission, that are direct or
8 indirect shareholders of the applicant shall be waived in the applicant's
9 disclosure of ownership and control as determined by the Commission.
10 (i) A pari-mutuel wagering device supplier license or a provisional pari-mutuel wagering
11 device supplier license shall be sufficient to offer pari-mutuel wagering devices for sale to a
12 legacy track operator and to a startup track operator.
13 (j) A person holding a pari-mutuel wagering device supplier license or its equivalent, on
14 the basis of comparable licensing requirements issued to that person by a proper authority by
15 another state or territory of the United States or the District of Columbia if that jurisdiction's
16 requirements for licensure, certification, or registration are substantially equivalent to or exceed
17 the requirements of this State, and who, in the opinion of the Commission otherwise meets the
18 requirements of this Article or of Article 9 of this Chapter, based upon verified evidence may,
19 upon application, be licensed as a pari-mutuel wagering device supplier with or without further
20 examination, as determined by the Commission.
21 (k) The Commission shall approve each pari-mutuel wagering device before it may be
22 sold by a pari-mutuel wagering device supplier to a legacy track operator or a startup track
23 operator; provided, however, pari-mutuel wagering devices that have been approved in other
24 states that allow for pari-mutuel wagering shall be approved by the Commission.
25 (l) Each pari-mutuel wagering device supplier shall promptly report all criminal or
26 disciplinary proceedings commenced against that pari-mutuel wagering device supplier in
27 connection with its operations to the Commission. Each pari-mutuel wagering device supplier
28 shall promptly report to the Commission all changes in key persons, and all new key persons
29 shall consent to a background investigation.
30 (m) No person shall offer a pari-mutuel wagering device available for use by the public
31 without a legacy track license or a startup track license.
32 "§ 18C-1007. Support for the North Carolina equine industry.
33 (a) There is hereby created a trust and revolving fund designated as the "Equine Breeders
34 Incentive Fund" for the purpose of providing rewards for breeders or owners of horses bred and
35 foaled in this State.
36 (1) The Equine Breeders Incentive Fund shall be administered by the
37 Commission, and the Commission shall promulgate administrative
38 regulations establishing the conditions and criteria for the distribution of
39 moneys from the fund that are consistent with this section.
40 (2) Revenues deposited in the Equine Breeders Incentive Fund shall be distributed
41 between two programs known as the Mare Incentive Program and the State
42 Bred Development Program. The Mare Incentive Program shall promote
43 horse farming and mare residency in this State, and the State Bred
44 Development Program shall promote North Carolina bred or initially owned
45 horses.
46 a. In years one and two of the Equine Breeders Incentive Fund, the
47 Commission shall allocate eighty percent (80%) of the revenues to the
48 Mare Incentive Program and twenty percent (20%) to the State Bred
49 Development Program.
50 b. In year three of the Equine Breeders Incentive Fund, the Commission
51 shall allocate seventy percent (70%) of the revenues to the Mare
DRS45254-BAxf-11 Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Incentive Program and thirty percent (30%) to the State Bred
2 Development Program.
3 c. In year four of the Equine Breeders Incentive Fund, the Commission
4 shall allocate sixty percent (60%) of the revenues to the Mare Incentive
5 Program and forty percent (40%) to the State Bred Development
6 Program.
7 d. In year five of the Equine Breeders Incentive Fund and in every year
8 thereafter, the Commission shall equally allocate the revenues
9 between the Mare Incentive Program and the State Bred Development
10 Program.
11 (3) On at least an annual basis, the Commission shall disburse to breeders or
12 owners of horses moneys in the fund to be used to promote, enhance, improve,
13 and encourage the further and continued development of the equine industry
14 in North Carolina, under the administrative regulations promulgated pursuant
15 to this section.
16 (b) There is hereby created a trust and revolving fund designated as the "Equine Industry
17 Purse Fund" for the purpose of promoting horse racing and to provide purses for races conducted
18 in this State.
19 (1) Funds maintained in the Equine Industry Purse Fund shall be distributed to
20 fund purses for live horse races of thoroughbred horses, standardbred horses,
21 and quarterhorses occurring at a legacy horse track or a startup horse track in
22 this State.
23 (2) The Commission shall promulgate administrative regulations that set forth the
24 allocation of funds held by the Equine Industry Purse Fund in a manner that
25 is consistent with this Article. Such allocation formula shall establish a
26 predictable means to fix the amount of money to be paid from the Equine
27 Industry Purse Fund to be added to the purse provided for a qualifying horse
28 race. At a minimum, eight-five percent (85%) of the Equine Industry Purse
29 Fund shall be distributed for purses of live horse races, including steeplechase
30 horse races, involving thoroughbred horses; ten percent (10%) of the Equine
31 Industry Purse Fund shall be distributed to purses of live horse races involving
32 standardbred horses; and the remainder shall be distributed to purses of live
33 horse races involving other breeds of horses.
34 (c) There is hereby created the Equine Programs Fund for the purposes of supporting the
35 equine industry and horses in this State.
36 (1) The Equine Programs Fund shall be distributed into three programs known as
37 Aftercare, North Carolina State Equine Veterinarian Programs, and the
38 National Steeplechase Association.
39 a. Aftercare programs shall be for the benefit of thoroughbreds,
40 standardbreds, and quarterhorses residing at aftercare facilities in
41 North Carolina. The Commission shall serve as the administrative
42 agent for these funds and shall distribute them at least annually to
43 organizations engaged in accreditation and monitoring of aftercare
44 facilities. Recipient programs shall award funds to aftercare facilities
45 based in this State that have achieved and maintained levels of service
46 and operation achieving national accreditation.
47 b. Funds distributed for the purpose of North Carolina State Equine
48 Veterinarian Programs shall be for research, workforce, and
49 operational grants to accredited equine veterinarian medicine
50 programs in this State.
Page 12 DRS45254-BAxf-11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 c. Funds distributed to the National Steeplechase Association shall be
2 used to promote and protect steeplechase races.
3 (2) The Commission shall create a formula and method for distributing funds to
4 the Equine Programs Fund through administrative regulation; provided,
5 however, the Commission shall divide Equine Programs Fund revenue as
6 follows:
7 a. Sixty-seven and one-half percent (67.5%) to North Carolina State
8 Veterinarian Programs.
9 b. Twenty percent (20%) to Aftercare programs.
10 c. The remainder to the National Steeplechase Association, Inc.
11 (d) Notwithstanding any provision to the contrary, all revenues in the funds created by
12 this section shall not revert but shall remain in each fund for purposes consistent with the fund.
13 "§ 18C-1008. General provisions for authorized horse races.
14 (a) The following acts are prohibited and may be punished as set forth in general law:
15 (1) No person shall knowingly enter or cause to be entered for competition, or
16 compete, for a prize or stake, or drive any horse, under an assumed name, or
17 out of its proper class, where the prize or stake is to be decided by a contest of
18 speed.
19 (2) No person shall change the name of any horse for the purpose of entry for
20 competition in any contest of speed, after the horse has once contested for a
21 prize or stake, except as provided by the code of rules of the association under
22 which the contest is advertised to be conducted.
23 (3) The class to which a horse belongs, for the purpose of an entry in any contest
24 of speed, shall be determined by the public performance of that horse in any
25 former contest or trial of speed, as provided by the rules of the Commission
26 under which the proposed contest is advertised to be conducted.
27 (4) No person shall knowingly misrepresent or fraudulently conceal the public
28 performance in any former contest, or trial of speed, of any horse that he
29 proposes to enter in a contest, whether the horse is actually entered or not.
30 (5) No person shall announce willfully and falsely a slower or faster time than the
31 time deemed actually accomplished by a horse in an official horse race.
32 (b) The pari-mutuel system of wagering on live or future horse races shall be operated
33 only by a totalizator or other mechanical equipment approved by the Commission and sold by a
34 pari-mutuel wagering device licensee. The Commission shall not require any particular make of
35 equipment.
36 (c) If the pari-mutuel wagering licensee so provides in its policies, and if such policies
37 are conspicuously posted on the pari-mutuel wagering licensee's website, any pari-mutuel ticket
38 issued by a pari-mutuel wagering licensee may be deemed abandoned if not collected within one
39 year of the date of purchase or date of relevant horse race, whichever is later. For tickets that are
40 deemed abandoned by operation of this subsection, on at least a quarterly basis, the pari-mutuel
41 wagering licensee shall pay to the Commission the value of the ticket, if any. The Commission
42 shall deposit all funds received pursuant to this subsection into the Equine Industry Purse Fund.
43 "§ 18C-1009. Administrative appeals and judicial review.
44 (a) If the Commission determines that the holder of a license issued under this Article
45 has violated any provision of this Article, the Commission may do any one or more of the
46 following after adhering to the procedures set forth in this section:
47 (1) Issue a formal warning and reprimand.
48 (2) Suspend the license.
49 (3) Revoke the license.
50 (4) Impose a monetary penalty of not more than ten thousand dollars ($10,000)
51 for each violation.
DRS45254-BAxf-11 Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) The following procedure shall apply in cases where the Commission determines that
2 a holder of a license issued pursuant to this Article has violated any provision of this Article:
3 (1) The Commission shall provide written notice to the licensee that does all of
4 the following:
5 a. Identifies the alleged conduct, the statute or regulation the conduct is
6 believed to have violated, and the proposed penalty for each alleged
7 violation.
8 b. Is sent by statutory overnight delivery to the registered address of the
9 licensee and, on the same day, also sent by electronic mail to the
10 licensee's corporate designee to receive notices from the Commission.
11 c. States that the allegation will be deemed admitted unless, within 30
12 days of the Commission's sending of the notice by statutory overnight
13 delivery, the licensee and Commission otherwise resolves the matter,
14 or the licensee appeals the notice as provided in this section.
15 (2) A licensee that has received a written notice described in this section may
16 appeal the allegation by commencing a contested case pursuant to Chapter
17 150B of the General Statutes. The appeal shall be commenced by the applicant
18 within 30 days of the date of receipt. Except as provided in subdivision (3) of
19 this subsection, the procedures set forth in Chapter 150 of the General Statutes
20 shall provide the exclusive mechanism for both administrative and judicial
21 review of the Commission's decision.
22 (3) If the Commission finds that the public health, safety, or welfare requires
23 emergency action, it may petition a court of competent jurisdiction for an
24 immediate injunction or other form of equitable relief, and in such matters,
25 the dispute will not be considered a contested case and subject to the
26 requirements of Chapter 150B of the General Statutes.
27 (c) Any applicant for a license issued pursuant to this Article that contends the
28 Commission wrongly denied or did not renew the applicant's license or renewal application may
29 seek administrative and judicial review pursuant to Chapter 150B of the General Statutes as a
30 contested case. The applicant must commence the appeal within 30 days of the Commission's
31 decision to deny or not renew the applicant's license.
32 (d) Nonpublic record documents and materials that applicants and licensees submit to the
33 Commission shall become public record if such materials are specifically identified by the
34 Commission as providing a basis for a civil penalty, license suspension, license revocation, or
35 other formal or informal enforcement action undertaken by the Commission against the licensee.
36 This subsection does not apply to any document that is identified in G.S. 132-1.2.
37 "§ 18C-1010. Annual fee for ADW licensees.License renewal.
38 (a) Each ADW licensee shall pay an annual fee to the Commission in order to maintain
39 their license. The fee is one percent (1%) of the total pari-mutuel wagers placed by residents of
40 this State accepted by the ADW licensee in the applicable year.All licenses issued pursuant to
41 this Article must be renewed every five years.
42 (1) Not less than four nor more than six months prior to the expiration of a license,
43 the Commission shall provide notice to the licensee of the date the license is
44 set to expire by electronic mail to the corporation's designee and by statutory
45 overnight delivery to the licensee's registered address.
46 (2) Any person with a license issued pursuant to this Article shall apply to the
47 Commission for renewal using a form prescribed by the Commission. The
48 form shall not seek any additional type of information than was required to
49 apply for the license.
50 (3) The Commission shall review and approve or deny applications for license
51 renewal within 30 days of receiving a complete renewal application; provided,
Page 14 DRS45254-BAxf-11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 however, the Commission may extend the review period one time for up to 30
2 days.
3 (4) The Commission shall renew any license application that continues to meet
4 the criteria for the license established by this Article; provided, however, the
5 Commission may deny an application for license renewal if the applicant's
6 license had been suspended twice during the prior five years, so long as the
7 suspensions were (i) not appealed or (ii) affirmed by last order of review.
8 (b) The fee shall be paid within four calendar weeks of the close of the ADW licensee's
9 fiscal or calendar year. The ADW licensee shall designate whether the annual fee required under
10 this section is payable on a fiscal year basis or a calendar year basis at the time the ADW licensee
11 applies for a license under G.S. 18C-1005. Once made, the designation is irrevocable during the
12 term of the license.An applicant seeking to renew a license issued pursuant to this Article shall
13 include with the renewal application a nonrefundable renewal fee as follows:
14 (1) For legacy track operators, startup track operators, and ADW licensees, two
15 hundred fifty thousand dollars ($250,000).
16 (2) For all other license renewals, fifteen thousand dollars ($15,000).
17 (c) The proceeds of any application fees and annual fees collected under this Article shall
18 be used to offset the cost of administering the provisions of this Article and Article 9 of this
19 Chapter. Any proceeds remaining at the end of each fiscal year after payment of expenses of the
20 Commission pursuant to this section shall be remitted to the General Fund, however, the
21 Commission may retain an amount reasonably necessary to cover future expenses of the
22 Commission related to administering the provisions of this Article and Article 9 of this Chapter,
23 the total of which, including the amount authorized to be retained under G.S. 18C-909, may not
24 exceed the total expenses of the Commission related to administering the provisions of this
25 Article and Article 9 of this Chapter during the previous quarter of the fiscal year.
26 (d) The Commission may suspend or revoke the license of an ADW licensee for failure
27 to timely pay the annual fee required under this section.
28 "§ 18C-1011. Relation of legacy track licenses and startup track licenses to other provisions
29 of law.
30 Notwithstanding any local government ordinance, rule, declaration, or regulation to the
31 contrary, a legacy track operator or startup track operator shall be entitled to operate the track
32 and any allowed satellite facility as authorized by this Article at the location and physical address
