34 "§ 18C-1012. Compact.
35 The Governor of this State is authorized to execute a compact on behalf of this State with any
36 of the United States, the District of Columbia, the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, and each
37 territory or possession of the United States, legally joining therein in the form substantially as
38 follows; provided, however, the compact shall not be effective as to this State unless it is
39 subsequently ratified by a simple majority vote of the House of Representatives and the Senate
40 within two years of the Governor's execution of the compact:
41 "ARTICLE I
42 PURPOSES
43 SECTION 1. PURPOSES.
44 The purposes of this compact are to:
45 1. Establish uniform requirements among the party states for the licensing of
46 participants in live racing with pari-mutuel wagering and ensure that all such
47 participants who are licensed pursuant to this compact meet a uniform
48 minimum standard of honesty and integrity.
49 2. Facilitate the growth of the pari-mutuel racing industry in each party state and
50 nationwide by simplifying the process for licensing participants in live racing,
51 and reduce the duplicative and costly process of separate licensing by the
DRS45254-BAxf-11 Page 15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 regulatory agency in each state that conducts live racing with pari-mutuel
2 wagering.
3 3. Authorize the North Carolina State Lottery Commission to participate in this
4 compact.
5 4. Provide for participation in this compact by officials of the party states, and
6 permit those officials, through the compact committee established by this
7 compact, to enter into contracts with governmental agencies and
8 nongovernmental persons to carry out the purposes of this compact.
9 5. Establish the compact committee created by this compact as an interstate
10 governmental entity duly authorized to request and receive criminal history
11 record information from the Federal Bureau of Investigation and other state
12 and local law enforcement agencies.
13 ARTICLE II
14 DEFINITIONS
15 SECTION 2. DEFINITIONS.
16 The following definitions apply in this Compact:
17 1. Compact committee. – The organization of officials from the party states that
18 is authorized and empowered by this compact to carry out the purposes of this
19 compact.
20 2. Official. – The appointed, elected, designated or otherwise duly selected
21 member of a racing commission or the equivalent thereof in a party state who
22 represents that party state as a member of the compact committee.
23 3. Participants in live racing. – Participants in live racing with pari-mutuel
24 wagering in the party states.
25 4. Party state. – Any state that has enacted this compact.
26 5. State. – Any of the several states of the United States, the District of Columbia,
27 the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico and each territory or possession of the
28 United States.
29 ARTICLE III
30 ENTRY INTO FORCE, ELIGIBLE PARTIES AND WITHDRAWAL
31 SECTION 3. ENTRY INTO FORCE.
32 This compact shall come into force when enacted by any four (4) states. Thereafter, this
33 compact shall become effective as to any other state upon both (i) that state's enactment of this
34 compact and (ii) the affirmative vote of a majority of the officials on the compact committee as
35 provided in Section 8.
36 SECTION 4. STATES ELIGIBLE TO JOIN COMPACT.
37 Any state that has adopted or authorized live racing with pari-mutuel wagering shall be
38 eligible to become party to this compact.
39 SECTION 5. WITHDRAWAL FROM COMPACT AND IMPACT THEREOF ON
40 FORCE AND EFFECT OF COMPACT.
41 Any party state may withdraw from this compact by enacting a statute repealing this compact,
42 but no such withdrawal shall become effective until the head of the executive branch of the
43 withdrawing state has given notice in writing of such withdrawal to the head of the executive
44 branch of all other party states. If as a result of withdrawals participation in this compact
45 decreases to less than three (3) party states, this compact no longer shall be in force and effect
46 unless and until there are at least three (3) or more party states again participating in this compact.
47 ARTICLE IV
48 COMPACT COMMITTEE
49 SECTION 6. COMPACT COMMITTEE ESTABLISHED.
50 There is hereby created an interstate governmental entity to be known as the "compact
51 committee," which shall be comprised of one (1) official from the racing commission or its
Page 16 DRS45254-BAxf-11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 equivalent in each party state who shall be appointed, serve and be subject to removal in
2 accordance with the laws of the party state he represents. Pursuant to the laws of his party state,
3 each official shall have the assistance of his state's racing commission or the equivalent thereof
4 in considering issues related to licensing of participants in live racing and in fulfilling his
5 responsibilities as the representative from his state to the compact committee. If an official is
6 unable to perform any duty in connection with the powers and duties of the compact committee,
7 the racing commission or equivalent thereof from his state shall designate another of its members
8 as an alternate who shall serve in his place and represent the party state as its official on the
9 compact committee until that racing commission or equivalent thereof determines that the
10 original representative official is able once again to perform his duties as that party state's
11 representative official on the compact committee. The designation of an alternate shall be
12 communicated by the affected state's racing commission or equivalent thereof to the compact
13 committee as the committee's bylaws may provide.
14 SECTION 7. POWERS AND DUTIES OF COMPACT COMMITTEE.
15 In order to carry out the purposes of this compact, the compact committee is hereby granted
16 the power and duty to:
17 1. Determine which categories of participants in live horse racing, including but
18 not limited to owners, trainers, jockeys, grooms, mutuel clerks, racing
19 officials, veterinarians, and farriers, and which categories of equivalent
20 participants in dog racing and other forms of live racing with pari-mutuel
21 wagering authorized in two (2) or more of the party states, should be licensed
22 by the committee, and establish the requirements for the initial licensure of
23 applicants in each such category, the term of the license for each category, and
24 the requirements for renewal of licenses in each category. Provided, however,
25 that with regard to requests for criminal history record information on each
26 applicant for a license, and with regard to the effect of a criminal record on
27 the issuance or renewal of a license, the compact committee shall determine
28 for each category of participants in live racing which licensure requirements
29 for that category are, in its judgment, the most restrictive licensure
30 requirements of any party state for that category and shall adopt licensure
31 requirements for that category that are, in its judgment, comparable to those
32 most restrictive requirements.
33 2. Investigate applicants for a license from the compact committee and, as
34 permitted by federal and state law, gather information on such applicants,
35 including criminal history record information from the Federal Bureau of
36 Investigation and relevant state and local law enforcement agencies, and,
37 where appropriate, from the Royal Canadian Mounted Police and law
38 enforcement agencies of other countries, necessary to determine whether a
39 license should be issued under the licensure requirements established by the
40 committee as provided in paragraph 1 above. Only officials on, and employees
41 of, the compact committee may receive and review such criminal history
42 record information, and those officials and employees may use that
43 information only for the purposes of this compact. No such official or
44 employee may disclose or disseminate such information to any person or
45 entity other than another official on or employee of the compact committee.
46 The fingerprints of each applicant for a license from the compact committee
47 shall be taken by the compact committee, its employees, or its designee and,
48 pursuant to Public Law 92-544 or Public Law 100-413, shall be forwarded to
49 a state identification bureau, or to an association of state officials regulating
50 pari-mutuel wagering designated by the Attorney General of the United States,
51 for submission to the Federal Bureau of Investigation for a criminal history
DRS45254-BAxf-11 Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 record check. Such fingerprints may be submitted on a fingerprint card or by
2 electronic or other means authorized by the Federal Bureau of Investigation
3 or other receiving law enforcement agency.
4 3. Issue licenses to, and renew the licenses of, participants in live racing listed in
5 paragraph 1 of this section who are found by the committee to have met the
6 licensure and renewal requirements established by the committee. The
7 compact committee shall not have the power or authority to deny a license. If
8 it determines that an applicant will not be eligible for the issuance or renewal
9 of a compact committee license, the compact committee shall notify the
10 applicant that it will not be able to process his application further. Such
11 notification does not constitute and shall not be considered to be the denial of
12 a license. Any such applicant shall have the right to present additional
13 evidence to, and to be heard by, the compact committee, but the final decision
14 on issuance or renewal of the license shall be made by the compact committee
15 using the requirements established pursuant to paragraph 1 of this section.
16 4. Enter into contracts or agreements with governmental agencies and with
17 nongovernmental persons to provide personal services for its activities and
18 such other services as may be necessary to effectuate the purposes of this
19 compact.
20 5. Create, appoint, and abolish those offices, employments, and positions,
21 including an executive director, as it deems necessary for the purposes of this
22 compact, prescribe their powers, duties and qualifications, hire persons to fill
23 those offices, employments and positions, and provide for the removal, term,
24 tenure, compensation, fringe benefits, retirement benefits and other conditions
25 of employment of its officers, employees and other positions.
26 6. Borrow, accept, or contract for the services of personnel from any state, the
27 United States, or any other governmental agency, or from any person, firm,
28 association, corporation or other entity.
29 7. Acquire, hold, and dispose of real and personal property by gift, purchase,
30 lease, license, or in other similar manner, in furtherance of the purposes of this
31 compact.
32 8. Charge a fee to each applicant for an initial license or renewal of a license.
33 9. Receive other funds through gifts, grants and appropriations.
34 SECTION 8. VOTING REQUIREMENTS.
35 A. Each official shall be entitled to one (1) vote on the compact committee.
36 B. All action taken by the compact committee with regard to the addition of party states
37 as provided in Section 3, the licensure of participants in live racing, and the receipt and
38 disbursement of funds shall require a majority vote of the total number of officials (or their
39 alternates) on the committee. All other action by the compact committee shall require a majority
40 vote of those officials (or their alternates) present and voting.
41 C. No action of the compact committee may be taken unless a quorum is present. A
42 majority of the officials (or their alternates) on the compact committee shall constitute a quorum.
43 SECTION 9. ADMINISTRATION AND MANAGEMENT.
44 A. The compact committee shall elect annually from among its members a chairman, a
45 vice chairman, and a secretary/treasurer.
46 B. The compact committee shall adopt bylaws for the conduct of its business by a
47 two-thirds (2/3) vote of the total number of officials (or their alternates) on the committee at that
48 time and shall have the power by the same vote to amend and rescind these bylaws. The
49 committee shall publish its bylaws in convenient form and shall file a copy thereof and a copy of
50 any amendments thereto with the Secretary of State or equivalent agency of each of the party
51 states.
Page 18 DRS45254-BAxf-11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 C. The compact committee may delegate the day-to-day management and administration
2 of its duties and responsibilities to an executive director and his support staff.
3 D. Employees of the compact committee shall be considered governmental employees.
4 SECTION 10. IMMUNITY FROM LIABILITY FOR PERFORMANCE OF OFFICIAL
5 RESPONSIBILITIES AND DUTIES.
6 No official of a party state or employee of the compact committee shall be held personally
7 liable for any good faith act or omission that occurs during the performance and within the scope
8 of his responsibilities and duties under this compact.
9 ARTICLE V
10 RIGHTS AND RESPONSIBILITIES OF EACH PARTY STATE
11 SECTION 11. RIGHTS AND RESPONSIBILITIES OF EACH PARTY STATE.
12 A. By enacting this compact, each party state:
13 1. Agrees (i) to accept the decisions of the compact committee regarding the
14 issuance of compact committee licenses to participants in live racing pursuant
15 to the committee's licensure requirements, and (ii) to reimburse or otherwise
16 pay the expenses of its official representative on the compact committee or his
17 alternate.
18 2. Agrees not to treat a notification to an applicant by the compact committee
19 under paragraph 3 of Section 7 that the compact committee will not be able to
20 process his application further as the denial of a license, or to penalize such
21 an applicant in any other way based solely on such a decision by the compact
22 committee.
23 3. Reserves the right (i) to charge a fee for the use of a compact committee
24 license in that state, (ii) to apply its own standards in determining whether, on
25 the facts of a particular case, a compact committee license should be
26 suspended or revoked, (iii) to apply its own standards in determining licensure
27 eligibility, under the laws of that party state, for categories of participants in
28 live racing that the compact committee determines not to license and for
29 individual participants in live racing who do not meet the licensure
30 requirements of the compact committee, and (iv) to establish its own licensure
31 standards for the licensure of nonracing employees at pari-mutuel racetracks
32 and employees to separate satellite wagering facilities. Any party state that
33 suspends or revokes a compact committee license shall, through its racing
34 commission or the equivalent thereof or otherwise, promptly notify the
35 compact committee of that suspension or revocation.
36 B. No party state shall be held liable for the debts or other financial obligations incurred
37 by the compact committee.
38 ARTICLE VI
39 CONSTRUCTION AND SEVERABILITY
40 SECTION 12. CONSTRUCTION AND SEVERABILITY.
41 This compact shall be liberally construed so as to effectuate its purposes. The provisions of
42 this compact shall be severable, and, if any phrase, clause, sentence, or provision of this compact
43 is declared to be contrary to the Constitution of the United States or of any party state, or the
44 applicability of this compact to any government, agency, person or circumstance is held invalid,
45 the validity of the remainder of this compact and the applicability thereof to any government,
46 agency, person or circumstance shall not be affected thereby. If all or some portion of this
47 compact is held to be contrary to the constitution of any party state, the compact shall remain in
48 full force and effect as to the remaining party states and in full force and effect as to the state
49 affected as to all severable matters."
50 "§ 18C-1013. Simulcasting.
DRS45254-BAxf-11 Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) Only legacy track operators and startup track operators may offer pari-mutuel
2 wagering on simulcasted horse races.
3 (b) Placing a pari-mutuel wager on an ADW wagering platform shall not be deemed
4 pari-mutuel wagering on simulcasted horse races.
5 (c) A track operator may offer pari-mutuel wagering on simulcasted horse races at only
6 the track and, as applicable, the satellite facility, identified in its track license.
7 (d) Every legacy track operator and startup track operator shall provide a separate
8 accounting on all interstate simulcasting to the Commission on a form and at such times, not
9 more than monthly, as required by the Commission.
10 (e) The use of an interstate common wagering pool is authorized. For purposes of this
11 subsection, an "interstate common wagering pool" means a pari-mutuel pool established in one
12 horse racing jurisdiction that is combined with comparable pari-mutuel pools from at least one
13 other horse racing jurisdiction for the purpose of establishing payoff prices in the various
14 jurisdictions.
15 (1) Interstate wagers made at a track may form an interstate common wagering
16 pool with wagers at a track in another jurisdiction, and the track may adopt
17 the commission and breakage rates of the track at which the race is being run.
18 The Commission may also approve types of wagering, distribution of
19 winnings, and rules of racing for interstate common wagering pools that are
20 different from those that normally apply in the State.
21 (2) Wagers placed on any races run at a legacy track or a startup track may be
22 combined with wagers placed at tracks in other jurisdictions to form an
23 interstate common wagering pool located either within or outside North
24 Carolina.
25 (3) A legacy track operator's or a startup track operator's participation in an
26 interstate common wagering pool does not cause the subject legacy track or
27 startup track to be considered to be doing business in any jurisdiction other
28 than the jurisdiction where the track is physically located. Excise taxes and
29 commission rates may not be imposed on any interstate common wagering
30 pool other than on amounts actually wagered in North Carolina. The
31 combination of pari-mutuel pools as provided in this section constitutes the
32 communication of wagering information for purposes of calculating odds and
33 payoffs only and does not constitute the transfer of wagers in interstate
34 commerce.
35 "§ 18C-1014. Transferability and assignability of pari-mutuel wagering licenses.
36 (a) Any license issued pursuant to this Article may be assigned or transferred to a third
37 party, pursuant to a sale or otherwise; provided, however, no such assignment or transfer shall
38 be effective until and unless the Commission approves the assignment or transfer as set forth in
39 this section.
40 (b) Before any person seeking to acquire a license issued pursuant to this Article by
41 assignment or transfer may take possession of the license, the licensee and the person to acquire
42 the license shall notify the Commission by submitting to the Commission a letter of intent of the
43 proposed transfer or assignment on a form prescribed by the Commission.
44 (c) Not less than 30 nor more than 45 days after providing the Commission with the letter
45 of intent, the person seeking to acquire the license shall submit an application to the Commission.
46 (1) An application for the acquisition of a legacy track license shall not be
47 approved by the Commission unless the applicant demonstrates that it satisfies
48 the criteria set forth in G.S. 18C-1003(b) and (c). Any transferred or assigned
49 legacy track license shall be under the same terms and conditions as the
50 original legacy track license.
Page 20 DRS45254-BAxf-11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) An application for the acquisition of a startup track license shall not be
2 approved by the Commission unless the applicant demonstrates that it satisfies
3 the criteria set forth in G.S. 18C-1004(b) and (e). Any transferred or assigned
4 startup track license shall be under the same terms and conditions as the
5 original startup track license.
6 (3) An application for the acquisition of an ADW license or a pari-mutuel
7 wagering device supplier license shall not be approved unless the Commission
8 determines the application satisfies all conditions of the original license.
9 "§ 18C-1015. Wagering.
10 (a) An individual resident of this State desiring to place pari-mutuel wagers through
11 means other than a pari-mutuel wagering device, a kiosk, or at a window shall establish an
12 account with an ADW licensee a pari-mutuel wagering licensee for that purpose. The ADW
13 pari-mutuel wagering licensee is responsible for verifying the identity of the individual and
14 ensuring that the individual is at least 21 years of age.
15 (b) The following are prohibited from engaging in pari-mutuel wagering under this
16 Article:
17 (1) Any person under the age of 21.
18 (2) Any person who has been adjudicated by law as prohibited from engaging in
19 pari-mutuel wagering.
20 (3) Any member or employee of the Commission. The Commission shall provide
21 a list of individuals subject to this subdivision to each ADW pari-mutuel
22 wagering licensee at least quarterly.
23 (4) Any person who has requested and not revoked a voluntary exclusion
24 designation from sports wagering pursuant to G.S. 18C-922. Participation in
25 the voluntary exclusion program shall not preclude an ADW a pari-mutuel
26 wagering licensee and its agents from seeking the payment of a debt accrued
27 by the individual while not participating in the voluntary exclusion program.
28 (c) An ADW A pari-mutuel wagering licensee shall make commercially reasonable
29 efforts to ensure that any prohibited person under this section is prevented from placing a
30 pari-mutuel wager with the ADW pari-mutuel wagering licensee.
31 (d) Any member of the Commission determined to have placed a pari-mutuel wager with
32 an ADW a pari-mutuel wagering licensee shall be deemed to have resigned from the Commission
33 as of the time the pari-mutuel wager is placed. Any employee of the Commission determined to
34 have placed a pari-mutuel wager with an ADW licensee is subject to disciplinary action.
35 (e) This Article does not authorize non-pari-mutuel wagering on the outcome of live,
36 simulcast, past, or any other horse races.
37 (f) The ADW licensee and their agents shall ensure that all advertisements and marketing
38 of advance deposit account wagering meet all of the following requirements:
39 (1) It does not target persons under the age of 21.
40 (2) It discloses the identity of the ADW pari-mutuel wagering licensee.
41 (3) It provides information about or links to resources related to gambling
42 addiction and prevention.
43 (4) It is not misleading to a reasonable person.
44 (5) It satisfies the rules and requirements promulgated by the Commission.
45 "§ 18C-1016. Amending licenses.
46 (a) By providing notice to the Commission, a legacy track operator or startup track
47 operator may relocate the track and, as applicable, the satellite facility, anywhere in the county
48 identified on the track license.
49 (b) No track operator may relocate a track pursuant to this section if such relocation
50 results in another track of the same license type falling within a 75-mile radius from the proposed
DRS45254-BAxf-11 Page 21

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 site of relocation. No legacy track operator shall relocate a satellite facility to any location that is
2 outside of a 20-mile radius of the legacy track.
3 "§ 18C-1017. Reports of the Commission.
4 (a) The Commission shall identify on its website the name and address of all legacy track
5 operators, startup track operators, ADW licensees, and pari-mutuel wagering device supplier
6 licensees.
7 (b) On an annual basis, the Commission shall report to the General Assembly the number
8 of authorized horse races taking place in this State, the type of horses competing at the horse
9 races, and the revenue generated for the General Fund and for each of the funds created by
10 G.S. 18C-1007 by pari-mutuel wagering at such horse races; provided, however, any such report
11 will separately identify revenue raised by the use of pari-mutuel wagering devices.
12 (c) Nothing in this section shall be deemed to limit the information the Commission may
13 provide.
14 "§ 18C-1018. (Reserved)
15 "§ 18C-1019. (Reserved)
16 "§ 18C-1020. Criminal penalties.
17 (a) Any person who knowingly offers or engages in pari-mutuel wagering in violation of
18 this Article shall be guilty of a Class 2 misdemeanor.
19 (b) Any person under the age of 21 who engages in pari-mutuel wagering as defined
20 under this Article shall be guilty of a Class 2 misdemeanor.
21 (c) Any person who knowingly attempts to suborn, collude, or otherwise conspire to
22 influence the outcome of any competition or aspect of any competition that is the subject of
23 pari-mutuel wagering pursuant to this Article shall be guilty of a Class G felony.
24 (d) Any person applying to become an ADW a pari-mutuel wagering licensee who
25 willfully furnishes, supplies, or otherwise gives false information on the license application shall
26 be guilty of a Class I felony.
27 (e) Nothing in this Article shall be construed to allow the ADW pari-mutuel wagering
28 licensee to be charged with a violation of subsection (a) or (c) of this section absent actual notice
29 and knowledge that a person is under age or giving false information.
30 "§ 18C-1021. (Reserved)
31 "§ 18C-1022. (Reserved)
32 "§ 18C-1023. (Reserved)
33 "§ 18C-1024. (Reserved)
34 "§ 18C-1025. Rulemaking.
35 (a) The Commission shall adopt rules governing the conduct of horse racing in this State,
36 which shall include rules regarding play of live horse racing and the placement of pari-mutuel
37 wagers on simulcast horse races. In adopting rules, the Commission shall consult the State
38 Veterinarian regarding safety of horses.
39 (b) When adopting rules, the Commission shall provide guidance on the issuance, denial,
40 suspension, or revocation of a license provided under this Article, on the operation of advance
41 deposit account wagering by ADW pari-mutuel wagering licensees, and on the requirements for
42 simulcast facilities."
43 SECTION 2.(a) Chapter 105 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
44 Article to read:
45 "Article 2F.
46 "Taxes on Pari-Mutuel Wagering.
47 "§ 105-113.150. Definitions.
48 The definitions of G.S. 18C-1001 and, to the extent they do not conflict, G.S. 18C-901, apply
49 in this Article.
50 "§ 105-113.151. Taxes on pari-mutuel wagering.
51 (a) Taxes. – The following taxes are imposed:
Page 22 DRS45254-BAxf-11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Pari-mutuel wagering devices. – A tax at the rate of twenty-nine percent (29%)
2 is imposed on each legacy track operator and startup track operator for the
3 privilege of being licensed under Article 10 of Chapter 18C of the General
4 Statutes. The tax applies to the adjusted gross revenue derived from
5 pari-mutuel wagering on all pari-mutuel wagering devices.
6 (2) Pari-mutuel wagering. – A tax rate of one and one-half percent (1.5%) is
7 imposed on each legacy track operator, startup track operator, and ADW
8 licensee for the privilege of being licensed under Article 10 of Chapter 18C
9 of the General Statutes. The tax applies to the total handle of each horse race
10 for which the pari-mutuel wagering licensee accepted pari-mutuel wagers;
11 provided, however, the tax does not apply to pari-mutuel wagers made on
12 pari-mutuel wagering devices. For purposes of the tax authorized by this
13 subdivision, the handle for each horse race shall include pari-mutuel wagers
14 made in person at a licensed legacy track, a satellite facility operated by a
15 legacy track operator, a licensed startup track, and pari-mutuel wagers made
16 through an advance deposit wagering account, regardless of whether the horse
17 race occurred in this State or in another jurisdiction.
18 (b) Return. – Taxes levied by this Article are due when a return is required to be filed.
19 The return is due on a monthly basis. A monthly return is due by the twentieth day of the month
20 following the calendar month covered by the return. The return shall be filed on a form prescribed
21 by the Secretary.
22 (c) Records. – A person required to file a return under this Article must keep a record of
23 all documents needed to verify the information in the return. The records shall be open at all
24 times for inspection by the Secretary or the Secretary's authorized representative and shall be
25 kept for the applicable period of statute of limitations as set forth under Article 9 of this Chapter.
26 (d) Refund. – A pari-mutuel wagering licensee is allowed a refund of any tax paid under
27 this section on a pari-mutuel wager that has been refunded. The Secretary shall prescribe the
28 manner in which a pari-mutuel wagering licensee may request a refund under this subsection,
29 which may include allowing a credit for the amount refunded on a subsequent monthly return
30 required under this section.
31 "§ 105-113.152. Registration and discontinuance requirements.
32 (a) Registration Required. – A pari-mutuel wagering licensee must register with the
33 Secretary.
34 (b) Registration Form. – Registration must be on a form prescribed by the Secretary and
35 include all information requested. If a pari-mutuel wagering licensee fails to register, the
36 Secretary must notify the Commission of the violation.
37 (c) Discontinuance of Authorized Activities. – A pari-mutuel wagering licensee who
38 changes ownership or stops engaging in the activities licensed under Article 10 of Chapter 18C
39 of the General Statutes must notify the Secretary in writing of the change.
40 "§ 105-113.153. Use of tax proceeds.
41 The Secretary shall distribute the taxes collected under this Article, less the allowance to the
42 Department of Revenue and reimbursement to the Commission for administrative expenses, in
43 accordance with this section. The Secretary may retain the cost of administering this Article, not
44 to exceed five hundred thousand dollars ($500,000) a year, as reimbursement to the Department.
45 The Commission shall, no later than 20 days after the end of the month, notify the Department
46 of its unreimbursed expenses from administering the provisions of Article 10 of Chapter 18C of
47 the General Statutes from the previous month. The Department shall reimburse the Commission
48 from the tax revenues collected under this Article no later than the end of the month in which the
49 Department was notified. The remaining proceeds shall be credited as follows:
50 (1) Net proceeds of the tax collected pursuant to G.S. 105-113.151(a)(1) shall be
51 credited as follows:
DRS45254-BAxf-11 Page 23

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. Sixty-nine percent (69%) to the General Fund.
2 b. Twenty-one percent (21%) to the Commission for allocation to the
3 Equine Industry Purse Fund created by G.S. 18C-1007.
4 c. Nine and one-half percent (9.5%) to the Commission for allocation to
5 the Equine Breeders Incentive Fund created by G.S. 18C-1007.
6 d. The remainder to the Commission for allocation to the Equine
7 Programs Fund created by G.S. 18C-1007.
8 (2) Net proceeds of the tax collected pursuant to G.S. 105-113.151(a)(2) shall be
9 credited as follows:
10 a. One-third (33.3%) to the Equine Industry Purse Fund;
11 b. One-third (33.3%) to the Equine Breeders Incentive Fund; and
12 c. The remaining funds split equally between the General Fund and the
13 Equine Programs Fund created by G.S. 18C-1007."
14 SECTION 2.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies to
15 pari-mutuel wagers received on or after that date.
